I was stranded in DC on a November night when my flight was diverted from EWR to Dulles due to a snowstorm.  By the time that I made my way to a hotel in downtown DC, it was fairly late.  While that wouldn't be a problem in, say, NYC, Washington restaurants aren't noted for their extended hours.  After walking around a bit in the freezing rain, I found Hank's.  I'm glad I did.  Despite the miserable weather, they had a number of customers.  The staff was very welcoming and the atmosphere cozy.  The entire menu looked good and it was difficult to settle on an entree.  I went with the New England Clam Chowder and the Fish & Chips, comfort foods that were well-prepared and delicious.  As the name of the restaurant implies, they've got an extensive menu of oysters, shrimp, clams, mussels and lobster.   They have a few meat dishes, but if you're not a seafood eater you should check the menu before deciding to go there to ensure that there's something that you like.

Stopped in for quick oysters and bloody Mary's on our way to a lunch. Josh at the bar is an incredibly charismatic and charming bartender and treated us like gold the whole time we were there despite being relatively busy. The oysters were incredible, and average pricing. Cocktails were good and beers were great. We will be back next time we visit DC to try the food and see if it's worth a fifth star!

This review is from a while ago, but my friends still talk about it, so I decided to write a review. My friend came to the DC area for her birthday and wanted a "DC brunch experience". She booked a reservation at another restaurant in Dupont, but they were super rude to us when we arrived, so we decided to leave. I called Hank's Oyster Bar and told them our dilemma. They told us we could come there immediately and be seated. The hostess and waitress were super friendly and gave great food recommendations. Everything was delicious, and they steadily refilled our mimosa glasses. At the end of our meal, the manager bought us shots and took lots of pictures for us. I am so thankful that they were able to make my friend's birthday brunch so amazing!

Hank's was a truly disappointing experience for me and both my dinner companions. The ambiance was a bit odd, as we were seated on the lower level in what felt like a cramped cave. The waitress was visibly annoyed that we didn't order any alcohol, and "joked" repeatedly about our failure to order drinks. Her service didn't improve over the course of the meal. When the food came, we each were visibly surprised at the small volume of food, given the price range of the entrees. Two of us remarked afterwards that we probably still had room for a whole big Mac meal. The quality of the food was fine. But not outstanding by any measure. After our meal, we lingered briefly at the table, chatting. After just a few minutes, I felt the eyes of our waitress and maitre d. I looked back and saw that they were anxious for us to vacate the table. I'm sensitive to the need of busy restaurants to turn tables over. But we had been there a mere 45 minutes. And the place had plenty of empty tables. I nudged my companions and suggested we vacate.  I'm honestly not sure how a place with pricey entrees, small portions, unimpressive food, and strangely poor service can stay in business in this part of DC. But Hank's proves that it indeed can.

The only positive note about Hank’s is the atmosphere. The service was fine, albeit slow; we were placed at a table directly in front of the coffee/water service station, despite multiple other tables being available (it was not a busy night). Once we changed tables and ordered, the food was substandard. The popcorn shrimp and calamari was average. After that, the lobster bisque was lukewarm, and a strong honey taste and smell was off-putting for a lobster bisque. The clam chowder was a thin white liquid with a few pieces of chopped potato and a clam or two. The rest of the dishes were no better, and were either not as described or tasteless (the po’boy could not be accepted as such by anyone who has had or seen a real po’boy). Overall I don’t understand the 4 stars given to this restaurant and won’t be coming back
